%[text] # R04: Protein-Ligand Analysis — Structure-Based Ligand Profiling
%[text] EasyMolKit Research — Layer 4
%[text] 
%[text] Drug repositioning is a strategy to explore whether a drug already approved for another disease can be effective for a new target.
%[text] Ligand-Based Virtual Screening (LBVS) is a method to narrow down candidates using only molecular fingerprints and physicochemical profiles without using a 3D docking simulator.
%[text] In this script, we score 200 FDA drugs using LBVS, referencing 5 types of approved kinase inhibitors, and output a report to identify promising repositioning candidates.
%[text] 
%[text] **Scope Note** 
%[text] Actual molecular docking (e.g., AutoDock, Glide) is not performed in this exercise. Instead, we implement an LBVS workflow combining 2D fingerprint similarity, physicochemical property matching, and sequence alignment using the Bioinformatics Toolbox.
%[text] **Learning Objectives**
%[text] - Understand the principles of LBVS and its differences from structure-based docking
%[text] - Profile the chemical space of approved kinase inhibitors using RDKit descriptors
%[text] - Design and implement a multi-criteria scoring function
%[text] - Analyze protein sequences with MATLAB Bioinformatics Toolbox
%[text] - Understand the difference between ligand efficiency and raw activity indicators \
%[text] **Prerequisites**
%[text] - Bioinformatics Toolbox
%[text] - Biopython: Please run `emk.setup.installExtra("biopython")` only once initially \
%[text] **Data**
%[text] - `data/list/fda_drugs.csv` — 200 FDA approved drugs (ChEMBL, CC-BY-SA 3.0)
%[text] - SMILES of reference kinase inhibitors are embedded in Section 1.
%[text] - PKA catalytic subunit FASTA (UniProt P17612) is embedded in Section 4. \
%[text] **References**
%[text] - Bleicher KH et al. (2003) Nat Rev Drug Discov 2:369-378. — LBVS and multi-criteria scoring
%[text] - Lipinski CA et al. (2001) Adv Drug Deliv Rev 46:3-26. — Ro5 and drug-likeness
%[text] - Hopkins AL & Groom CR (2002) Nat Rev Drug Discov 1:727-730. — Concept of ligand efficiency
%[text] - Rogers D & Hahn M (2010) J Chem Inf Model 50:742-754. — ECFP4 fingerprints
%[text] - Cock PJA et al. (2009) Bioinformatics 25:1422-1423. — Biopython \
%[text] Duration: 45–90 minutes | Execution: Run each section with Ctrl+Enter.
%%
%[text] ## Section 0: Setup
% Resolve project root (works for Desktop, MCP, and MATLAB Online)
sDir = fileparts(mfilename('fullpath'));
if strlength(sDir) > 0
    addpath(genpath(fullfile(sDir, '..', '..', '..', 'src')));
elseif isfolder(fullfile(pwd, 'src'))
    addpath(genpath(fullfile(pwd, 'src')));
elseif ~isempty(which("logInfo"))
    addpath(genpath(fileparts(fileparts(which("logInfo")))));
end
projectRoot = resolveProjectRoot();
addpath(genpath(fullfile(projectRoot, 'src')));
emk.setup.initPython(); %[output:2e78f9d0]
%[text] Warming up Python/RDKit process.
mol_warmup = emk.mol.fromSmiles("C");
clear mol_warmup;
%[text] Checking for Bioinformatics Toolbox.
hasBioTbx = license("test", "bioinformatics_toolbox");
if hasBioTbx %[output:group:25fac20a]
    logInfo("R04: Bioinformatics Toolbox detected."); %[output:86ea0a0d]
else
    logWarn("R04: Bioinformatics Toolbox not found. Section 4 will use manual fallback.");
end %[output:group:25fac20a]
%[text] Checking for Biopython.
bpAvailable = false;
try %[output:group:3b4180f6]
    py.importlib.import_module("Bio");
    bpAvailable = true;
    logInfo("R04: Biopython detected."); %[output:1853dabb]
catch
    logWarn("R04: Biopython not found. Please run emk.setup.installExtra(""biopython"").");
end %[output:group:3b4180f6]
logInfo("R04: Setup complete."); %[output:9c021d05]
%%
%[text] ## Section 1: Profiling the Chemical Space of Kinase Inhibitors
%[text] ### Principle of Ligand-Based Virtual Screening (LBVS)
%[text] Structure-based docking requires a 3D protein structure and docking software.
%[text] When neither is available, LBVS offers an alternative grounded in the similarity-property principle (Johnson & Maggiora 1990): structurally similar molecules tend to share bioactivity.
%[text] LBVS proceeds in three steps:
%[text] 1. Select a known active ligand (reference inhibitor)
%[text] 2. Score all candidates by structural similarity to the reference
%[text] 3. Rank candidates and prioritize the highest-scoring ones \
%[text] In this section, we calculate the physicochemical footprint of the five approved kinase inhibitors below to define the screening reference space.
%[text:table]{"ignoreHeader":true}
%[text] | Drug Name | Target | Inhibitor Class |
%[text] | --- | --- | --- |
%[text] | Imatinib | BCR-ABL / c-KIT / PDGFR | First-generation TKI |
%[text] | Erlotinib | EGFR | EGFR Inhibitor |
%[text] | Gefitinib | EGFR | EGFR Inhibitor |
%[text] | Dasatinib | BCR-ABL / Src | Multi-kinase Inhibitor |
%[text] | Sorafenib | RAF / VEGFR / PDGFR | Multi-kinase Inhibitor |
%[text:table]
%[text] 
%[text] These 5 drugs represent a diverse range of kinase inhibitors spanning Type I / II / III binding modes and will be used as LBVS queries.
REF_NAMES  = ["Imatinib", "Erlotinib", "Gefitinib", "Dasatinib", "Sorafenib"];
REF_SMILES = [ ...
    "Cc1ccc(cc1Nc2nccc(n2)c3cccnc3)NC(=O)c4ccc(cc4)CN5CCN(CC5)C", ...  % Imatinib
    "C#Cc1cccc(c1)Nc2ncnc3cc(OCCOC)c(OCCOC)cc23",                       ...  % Erlotinib
    "COc1cc2ncnc(Nc3ccc(F)c(Cl)c3)c2cc1OCCCN4CCOCC4",                  ...  % Gefitinib
    "Cc1nc(Nc2ncc(s2)C(=O)Nc3c(C)cccc3Cl)cc(n1)N4CCN(CCO)CC4",        ...  % Dasatinib
    "CNC(=O)c1cc(ccn1)Oc2ccc(cc2)NC(=O)Nc3ccc(c(c3)C(F)(F)F)Cl"       ...  % Sorafenib
    ];
FP_RADIUS = 2;
FP_NBITS  = 2048;
%[text] Parse the reference inhibitors and calculate descriptors and fingerprints.
nRef      = numel(REF_NAMES);
refMols   = cell(1, nRef);
refFps    = cell(1, nRef);
refValid  = false(1, nRef);
for k = 1:nRef
    try
        refMols{k}  = emk.mol.fromSmiles(REF_SMILES(k));
        refFps{k}   = emk.fingerprint.morgan(refMols{k}, Radius=FP_RADIUS, NBits=FP_NBITS);
        refValid(k) = true;
    catch ex
        logWarn("R04: Failed to parse %s: %s", REF_NAMES(k), ex.message);
    end
end
validRef  = find(refValid);
refMols   = refMols(validRef);
refFps    = refFps(validRef);
refNames  = REF_NAMES(validRef);
nRefValid = numel(validRef);
logInfo("R04 Sec1: Parsed %d / %d reference kinase inhibitors.", nRefValid, nRef); %[output:478d9f99]
%[text] Calculate the physicochemical descriptors of the reference inhibitors.
DESCS      = ["MolWt", "LogP", "TPSA", "NumHDonors", "NumHAcceptors", "NumRotatableBonds"];
refDescTbl = emk.descriptor.batchCalculate(refMols, DESCS);
refDescTbl.Name = refNames';
logInfo("Physicochemical profile of kinase inhibitors:"); %[output:5ea4cbac]
logInfo("  %-12s  %6s  %5s  %6s  %4s  %4s  %4s", ... %[output:group:1c857b2e] %[output:1f7aeafc]
    "Name", "MolWt", "LogP", "TPSA", "HBD", "HBA", "RotB"); %[output:group:1c857b2e] %[output:1f7aeafc]
for k = 1:height(refDescTbl) %[output:group:837ee193]
    logInfo("  %-12s  %6.1f  %5.2f  %6.1f  %4.0f  %4.0f  %4.0f", ... %[output:9f905cb5]
        refNames(k), ... %[output:9f905cb5]
        refDescTbl.MolWt(k), refDescTbl.LogP(k), refDescTbl.TPSA(k), ... %[output:9f905cb5]
        refDescTbl.NumHDonors(k), refDescTbl.NumHAcceptors(k), ... %[output:9f905cb5]
        refDescTbl.NumRotatableBonds(k)); %[output:9f905cb5]
end %[output:group:837ee193]
%[text] Calculate the median profile of reference KI for later scoring.
kiMedian.MolWt             = median(refDescTbl.MolWt);
kiMedian.LogP              = median(refDescTbl.LogP);
kiMedian.TPSA              = median(refDescTbl.TPSA);
kiMedian.NumHDonors        = median(refDescTbl.NumHDonors);
kiMedian.NumHAcceptors     = median(refDescTbl.NumHAcceptors);
kiMedian.NumRotatableBonds = median(refDescTbl.NumRotatableBonds);
logInfo("Reference KI median: MW=%.0f, LogP=%.2f, TPSA=%.0f", ... %[output:group:6f74f4cd] %[output:60a58f74]
    kiMedian.MolWt, kiMedian.LogP, kiMedian.TPSA); %[output:group:6f74f4cd] %[output:60a58f74]
%[text] **How to Read the Figure** Each axis shows a property normalized by its upper limit (e.g., MW/600).
%[text] Similar polygon shapes across the 5 drugs indicate that they occupy a compact, homogeneous region of chemical space.
figure("Name", "R04 Sec1: Kinase Inhibitor Property Profile"); %[output:11ab4f49]
propMat_ref = [refDescTbl.MolWt/600, ...
               (refDescTbl.LogP + 2) / 8, ...
               refDescTbl.TPSA / 200, ...
               refDescTbl.NumHDonors / 6, ...
               refDescTbl.NumHAcceptors / 12, ...
               refDescTbl.NumRotatableBonds / 14];
axLabels = ["MW_600", "LogP_8", "TPSA_200", "HBD_6", "HBA_12", "RotB_14"];
propTbl_ref = array2table(propMat_ref, VariableNames=cellstr(axLabels));
propTbl_ref.Inhibitor = refNames';
parallelplot(propTbl_ref, GroupVariable="Inhibitor"); %[output:11ab4f49]
title("Kinase Inhibitor Normalized Property Profile"); %[output:11ab4f49]
%%
%[text] ## Section 2: FDA Drug Library Screening by Fingerprint Similarity
%[text] ### The Tanimoto Coefficient
%[text] A molecular fingerprint is a bit string where each bit encodes the presence or absence of a specific substructure.
%[text] The Tanimoto coefficient between two fingerprints $q$ (query) and $d$ (database molecule) is:
%[text]{"align":"center"} $T(q, d) = \\frac{|q \\cap d|}{|q \\cup d|}$
%[text] where $|q \\cap d|$ is the number of bits set in both and $|q \\cup d|$ is the number set in either. $T$ ranges from 0 (no overlap) to 1 (identical), with higher values indicating greater structural similarity.
%[text] In drug discovery, $T \> 0.85$ is the conventional threshold for "close analogs"; here we also use 0.40 and 0.50 as reference cutoffs.
%[text] For each FDA drug, we define the maximum Tanimoto similarity across all five reference KIs as:
%[text]{"align":"center"} $\\text{maxSim}(c) = \\max \\{ T(c,\\, r(k)) \\mid k = 1, \\ldots, K \\}$
%[text] where $r(k)$ is the fingerprint of the $k$-th reference KI.
%[text] A higher $\\text{maxSim}$ places the candidate closer to the known KI chemical space.
DATA_FILE = "data/list/fda_drugs.csv";
rawTbl    = readtable(DATA_FILE, TextType="string");
logInfo("R04 Sec2: Loaded %d entries from %s.", height(rawTbl), DATA_FILE); %[output:88a38408]
nLib  = height(rawTbl);
mols  = cell(1, nLib);
fps   = cell(1, nLib);
valid = false(1, nLib);
for k = 1:nLib %[output:group:3330efbc]
    try
        mols{k}  = emk.mol.fromSmiles(rawTbl.SMILES(k));
        fps{k}   = emk.fingerprint.morgan(mols{k}, Radius=FP_RADIUS, NBits=FP_NBITS);
        valid(k) = true;
    catch
        % skip unparseable entries silently
    end
    if mod(k, 20) == 0 || k == nLib
        logProgress(k, nLib, "Fingerprinting FDA library"); %[output:72e5c800]
    end
end %[output:group:3330efbc]
validIdx  = find(valid);
mols      = mols(validIdx);
fps       = fps(validIdx);
libNames  = rawTbl.Name(validIdx);
libSmiles = rawTbl.SMILES(validIdx);
nValid    = numel(validIdx);
logInfo("R04 Sec2: Parsed %d / %d molecules.", nValid, nLib); %[output:3e6354db]
%[text] Using `emk.similarity.rankBy`, calculate the similarity of the entire library for each reference KI.
maxSimScores = zeros(nValid, 1);
simMatrix    = zeros(nValid, nRefValid);
for r = 1:nRefValid
    result = emk.similarity.rankBy(refFps{r}, fps, Inf, Metric="tanimoto");
    simMatrix(result.Indices, r) = result.Scores;
end
maxSimScores = max(simMatrix, [], 2);
bestRefIdx   = zeros(nValid, 1);
for k = 1:nValid
    [~, bestRefIdx(k)] = max(simMatrix(k, :));
end
bestRefName  = refNames(bestRefIdx)';
logInfo("R04 Sec2: Distribution of maximum similarity:"); %[output:96b9226d]
logInfo("  > 0.70 (close analogs)         : %d", sum(maxSimScores > 0.70)); %[output:7f83905b]
logInfo("  > 0.50 (neighboring molecules) : %d", sum(maxSimScores > 0.50)); %[output:217d34b7]
logInfo("  > 0.40 (same scaffold)         : %d", sum(maxSimScores > 0.40)); %[output:230ce3ef]
%[text] **How to Read the Figure** Drugs on the right tail are close to the KI chemical space -- the primary candidates of interest.
figure("Name", "R04 Sec2: Max Tanimoto Similarity to Kinase Inhibitors"); %[output:66021ae6]
histogram(maxSimScores, 30, FaceColor=[0.2 0.5 0.8], FaceAlpha=0.7); %[output:66021ae6]
xline(0.40, "r--", "LineWidth", 1.5, DisplayName="0.40 Threshold"); %[output:66021ae6]
xline(0.50, "g--", "LineWidth", 1.5, DisplayName="0.50 Threshold"); %[output:66021ae6]
xlabel("Max Tanimoto Similarity to Reference KIs"); %[output:66021ae6]
ylabel("Number of Compounds"); %[output:66021ae6]
title("FDA Drugs vs Kinase Inhibitor Chemical Space"); %[output:66021ae6]
legend(Location="best"); %[output:66021ae6]
%[text] **Note** The FDA library includes Erlotinib (free base form) with the same SMILES as in the reference set, so its Tanimoto score is 1.0 (exact match). This functions as a positive control: a known EGFR inhibitor should always be a top hit.
%%
%[text] ## Section 3: Composite Kinase-Ligand Scoring
%[text] ### Design of Multi-Criteria Scoring Function
%[text] Tanimoto similarity alone is not enough to prioritize drug candidates -- it says nothing about ADMET properties. We therefore build a composite score combining three orthogonal signals.
%[text] 
%[text] **Component 1: Structural Similarity Score** $S(\\text{sim})$ **(Weight 0.4)**
%[text] Captures whether the candidate is structurally close to a known KI.
%[text] We use $\\text{maxSim}$ from Section 2 directly (range $\[0, 1\]$), giving it the highest weight because structural similarity has the strongest predictive signal for active-class membership.
%[text] 
%[text] **Component 2: Physicochemical Property Match** $S(\\text{prop})$ **(Weight 0.4)**
%[text] Measures how closely the candidate's MW, LogP, and TPSA match the median profile of reference KIs via a Gaussian kernel: $g(x) = \\exp\\!\\left( -\\frac{(x - \\bar{x})^2}{2\\sigma^2} \\right)$, averaged over the three properties.
%[text] Typical kinase inhibitor ranges are MW 400--550 g/mol, LogP 2.0--4.5, TPSA 60--140 A^2 -- broader than the classical Lipinski Ro5, which is why kinase inhibitors are sometimes called "bRo5 (beyond Ro5)" compounds.
%[text] 
%[text] **Component 3: Ligand Efficiency Proxy (LE) (Weight 0.2)**
%[text] Ligand efficiency is potency per heavy atom -- a measure of how efficiently the molecule uses its size to drive activity. Without a measured IC50, we use a physicochemical proxy from Hopkins et al. (2004):
%[text]{"align":"center"} $\\text{LE} = \\frac{\\exp( -|\\text{LogP} - 3.0| / 2 )}{\\text{MW} / 300}$
%[text] A LogP near 3.0 (the permeability-solubility optimum) and a small MW push LE toward 1.0. An ideal efficient ligand (MW = 300, LogP = 3.0) gives $\\text{LE} \\to 1.0$.
%[text] 
%[text] **Composite Score**
%[text]{"align":"center"} $\\text{Score} = 0.4 \\times S(\\text{sim}) + 0.4 \\times S(\\text{prop}) + 0.2 \\times \\text{LE}$
%[text] All three components are bounded in $\[0, 1\]$, so the maximum possible score is 1.0 (weights sum to 1).
libDescTbl = emk.descriptor.batchCalculate(mols, DESCS);
S_sim = maxSimScores;
%[text] The Gaussian width $\\sigma$ is set based on the spread of the chemical space of approved KIs (MW: 80 g/mol, LogP: 1.5, TPSA: 40 Å²).
sigma_MW   = 80.0;
sigma_LogP = 1.5;
sigma_TPSA = 40.0;
gMW   = exp(-0.5 * ((libDescTbl.MolWt  - kiMedian.MolWt)  / sigma_MW)  .^2);
gLogP = exp(-0.5 * ((libDescTbl.LogP   - kiMedian.LogP)   / sigma_LogP).^2);
gTPSA = exp(-0.5 * ((libDescTbl.TPSA   - kiMedian.TPSA)   / sigma_TPSA).^2);
S_prop = (gMW + gLogP + gTPSA) / 3;
%[text] Clamping is performed to prevent MW from becoming a minimum value (usually unnecessary for FDA data).
mw_safe  = max(libDescTbl.MolWt, 50);
LE_proxy = exp(-abs(libDescTbl.LogP - 3.0) / 2) ./ (mw_safe / 300);
LE_proxy = min(LE_proxy, 1.0);
LE_proxy = max(LE_proxy, 0.0);
W_SIM  = 0.4;
W_PROP = 0.4;
W_LE   = 0.2;
compositeScore = W_SIM * S_sim + W_PROP * S_prop + W_LE * LE_proxy;
%[text] Sort the result table in descending order of composite score.
resultTbl = table(libNames, libSmiles, maxSimScores, bestRefName, ...
    libDescTbl.MolWt, libDescTbl.LogP, libDescTbl.TPSA, ...
    libDescTbl.NumHDonors, libDescTbl.NumHAcceptors, ...
    S_sim, S_prop, LE_proxy, compositeScore, ...
    VariableNames=["Name", "SMILES", "MaxSim", "BestRefKI", ...
        "MolWt", "LogP", "TPSA", "HBD", "HBA", ...
        "Score_Sim", "Score_Prop", "Score_LE", "CompositeScore"]);
resultTbl = sortrows(resultTbl, "CompositeScore", "descend");
logInfo("R04 Sec3: Top 10 Kinase-Ligand Candidates:"); %[output:97e210fc]
logInfo("  %-20s  %5s  %5s  %5s  %5s  %5s  %7s", ... %[output:group:7649690e] %[output:632047ca]
    "Name", "MW", "LogP", "TPSA", "Sim", "Prop", "Total"); %[output:group:7649690e] %[output:632047ca]
for k = 1:min(10, height(resultTbl)) %[output:group:0253fb14]
    logInfo("  %-20s  %5.0f  %5.2f  %5.0f  %5.3f  %5.3f  %7.4f", ... %[output:62dbfae3]
        resultTbl.Name(k), resultTbl.MolWt(k), resultTbl.LogP(k), ... %[output:62dbfae3]
        resultTbl.TPSA(k), resultTbl.Score_Sim(k), resultTbl.Score_Prop(k), ... %[output:62dbfae3]
        resultTbl.CompositeScore(k)); %[output:62dbfae3]
end %[output:group:0253fb14]
%[text] **How to Read the Chart** Each color in the stacked bar graph indicates the contribution of component scores (Blue: Similarity, Orange: Property Match, Green: LE Proxy).
top20 = resultTbl(1:min(20, height(resultTbl)), :);
figure("Name", "R04 Sec3: Composite Score Decomposition -- Top 20"); %[output:7eec60ee]
set(gcf, "Position", [100, 100, 900, 420]); %[output:7eec60ee]
barData = [top20.Score_Sim, top20.Score_Prop, top20.Score_LE];
b = bar(barData, "stacked"); %[output:7eec60ee]
b(1).FaceColor = [0.2 0.5 0.8]; %[output:7eec60ee]
b(2).FaceColor = [0.8 0.4 0.2]; %[output:7eec60ee]
b(3).FaceColor = [0.3 0.7 0.3]; %[output:7eec60ee]
xticks(1:height(top20)); %[output:7eec60ee]
xticklabels(top20.Name); %[output:7eec60ee]
xtickangle(45); %[output:7eec60ee]
ylabel("Score Components (Raw Values, Unweighted)"); %[output:7eec60ee]
title("Kinase-Ligand Composite Score — Top 20 FDA Drugs"); %[output:7eec60ee]
legend(["Similarity (w=0.4)", "Property Match (w=0.4)", "LE Proxy (w=0.2)"], ... %[output:group:9aee7da9] %[output:7eec60ee]
    Location="northeast"); %[output:group:9aee7da9] %[output:7eec60ee]
%[text] Check the correlation between similarity score and property match score in a scatter plot.
%[text] Compounds in the upper-right quadrant (high scores on both axes) are the most promising candidates.
figure("Name", "R04 Sec3: Similarity vs Property Match Score"); %[output:460ee698]
scatter(S_sim, S_prop, 30, compositeScore, "filled", MarkerFaceAlpha=0.6); %[output:460ee698]
cb = colorbar(); %[output:460ee698]
cb.Label.String = "Composite Score"; %[output:460ee698]
xlabel("Similarity Score S(sim)"); %[output:460ee698]
ylabel("Property Match Score S(prop)"); %[output:460ee698]
title("Overview of FDA Drug Scoring"); %[output:460ee698]
xline(0.40, "r--", DisplayName="Sim = 0.40"); %[output:460ee698]
yline(0.40, "b--", DisplayName="Prop = 0.40"); %[output:460ee698]
legend(Location="best"); %[output:460ee698]
%%
%[text] ## Section 4: Protein Sequence Annotation (Bioinformatics Toolbox + Biopython)
%[text] ### Conserved Sequence Features of Kinase Binding Pockets
%[text] Protein kinase ATP binding sites contain highly conserved amino acid motifs. The "DFG motif" (Asp-Phe-Gly) in the activation loop is a hallmark of all kinases.
%[text] In the DFG-In conformation, classical ATP-competitive (Type I) inhibitors bind; in the DFG-Out conformation, Type II inhibitors such as Imatinib and Sorafenib extend into the "back pocket."
%[text] The P-loop (phosphate-binding loop) is another key conserved motif, with consensus sequence "GxGxxG" (x = any residue) that anchors the $\\beta$-phosphate of ATP.
%[text] In PKA, residues 51--56 (GTGSFG) correspond to this consensus.
%[text] 
%[text] We analyze the FASTA sequence of human PKA catalytic subunit $\\alpha$ (UniProt P17612, 351 residues) to locate the DFG motif and P-loop. The sequence is embedded in the script -- no internet connection required.
PKA_FASTA_HEADER  = "sp|P17612|KAPCA_HUMAN cAMP-dependent protein kinase catalytic subunit alpha";
PKA_FASTA_SEQ     = strjoin([ ...
    "MGNAAAAKKGSEQESVKEFLAKAKEDFLKKWENPAQNTAHLDQFERIKTLGTGSFGRVML" ...
    "VKHKETGNHYAMKILDKQKVVKLKQIEHTLNEKRILQAVNFPFLVKLEFSFKDNSNLYM" ...
    "VMEYVAGGEMFSHLRRIGRFSEPHARFYAAQIVLTFEYLHSLDLIYRDLKPENLLIDQQG" ...
    "YIQVTDFGFAKRVKGRTWTLCGTPEYLAPEIILSKGYNKAVDWWALGVLIYEMAAGYPPF" ...
    "FADQPIQIYEKIVSGKVRFPSHFSSDLKDLLRNLLQVDLTKRFGNLKNGVNDIKNHKWFA" ...
    "TTDWIAIYQRKVEAPFIPKFKGPGDTSNFDDYEEEEIRVSINEKCGKEFSEF" ...
    ], "");
DFG_MOTIF = "DFG";
logInfo("R04 Sec4: Starting kinase sequence analysis."); %[output:4fa9135f]
logInfo("  Sequence : %s", PKA_FASTA_HEADER); %[output:373fdb70]
logInfo("  Length : %d residues", strlength(PKA_FASTA_SEQ)); %[output:07eac810]
%[text] Identify the position of the DFG motif using MATLAB string search.
dfgPos = strfind(char(PKA_FASTA_SEQ), char(DFG_MOTIF));
if ~isempty(dfgPos) %[output:group:572f4d70]
    logInfo("  Detected DFG motif at position %d: ...%s...", dfgPos(1), ... %[output:257040fc]
        extractBetween(PKA_FASTA_SEQ, max(1, dfgPos(1)-5), ... %[output:257040fc]
            min(strlength(PKA_FASTA_SEQ), dfgPos(1)+7))); %[output:257040fc]
else
    logWarn("  DFG motif not found. Please check the sequence.");
end %[output:group:572f4d70]
%[text] If Biopython is available, count amino acid composition and check charged residues.
%[text] The number of charged residues (D, E, K, R, H) reflects the electrostatic properties of the ATP binding site.
if bpAvailable %[output:group:8e38d383]
    try
        bioSeq    = py.Bio.Seq.Seq(PKA_FASTA_SEQ);
        aaCountPy = py.collections.Counter(char(PKA_FASTA_SEQ));
        aaCountKeys = cell(py.list(aaCountPy.keys()));
        aaCountVals = cell(py.list(aaCountPy.values()));
        aaComp = struct();
        for ai = 1:numel(aaCountKeys)
            aa = string(aaCountKeys{ai});
            if ~isempty(regexp(aa, "^[A-Z]$", "once"))
                aaComp.(aa) = double(aaCountVals{ai});
            end
        end
        chargedAA = ["D", "E", "K", "R", "H"];
        logInfo("  Number of charged residues (related to ATP binding):"); %[output:56254386]
        for ai = 1:numel(chargedAA)
            aa = chargedAA(ai);
            if isfield(aaComp, aa)
                logInfo("    %s : %d", aa, aaComp.(aa)); %[output:656987d9]
            end
        end
        logInfo("  Biopython sequence analysis completed."); %[output:02b0a75d]
    catch ex
        logWarn("R04 Sec4: Biopython analysis failed: %s", ex.message);
    end
else
    logWarn("R04 Sec4: Biopython is not available. Please run emk.setup.installExtra(""biopython"").");
end %[output:group:8e38d383]
%[text] If the Bioinformatics Toolbox is available, we search for the P-loop using Smith-Waterman local alignment -- an algorithm that finds the best-matching sub-sequence rather than aligning full sequences end-to-end.
if hasBioTbx %[output:group:1f8e3896]
    try
        PLOOP_PROBE = "GSGSFGRVM";
        seqStr      = char(PKA_FASTA_SEQ);
        [score, alignStr] = swalign(seqStr, char(PLOOP_PROBE), "alphabet", "AA");
        logInfo("  P-loop alignment score = %.1f", score); %[output:43a4f75c]
        logInfo("  Alignment: %s", string(alignStr(1, :))); %[output:801df30e]
        logInfo("  P-loop annotation completed."); %[output:307f2dc9]
    catch ex
        logWarn("R04 Sec4: swalign failed: %s", ex.message);
    end
else
    logInfo("  Bioinformatics Toolbox is not available. Performing manual motif scan.");
    PLOOP_MOTIF = "GTGSFG";
    pPos = strfind(char(PKA_FASTA_SEQ), char(PLOOP_MOTIF));
    if ~isempty(pPos)
        logInfo("  Detected P-loop motif '%s' at position %d.", PLOOP_MOTIF, pPos(1));
    else
        pPos2 = strfind(char(PKA_FASTA_SEQ), "GSFG");
        if ~isempty(pPos2)
            logInfo("  Detected partial match P-loop 'GSFG' at position %d.", pPos2(1));
        else
            logWarn("  P-loop motif not found. Please check the sequence.");
        end
    end
end %[output:group:1f8e3896]
%[text] **How to Read the Figure** The bar graph shows the amino acid frequency distribution.
%[text] Kinases typically show elevated counts of D (Asp), E (Glu), K (Lys), and R (Arg), reflecting their reliance on charged residues for ATP binding.
figure("Name", "R04 Sec4: PKA Sequence Residue Composition"); %[output:4d7086bd]
aaOrder     = "ACDEFGHIKLMNPQRSTVWY";
aaOrderChar = char(aaOrder);
aaFreq      = zeros(1, numel(aaOrderChar));
seqChar     = char(PKA_FASTA_SEQ);
for ai = 1:numel(aaOrderChar)
    aaFreq(ai) = sum(seqChar == aaOrderChar(ai));
end
bar(aaFreq, FaceColor=[0.4 0.6 0.8]); %[output:4d7086bd]
xticks(1:numel(aaOrderChar)); %[output:4d7086bd]
xticklabels(cellstr(aaOrderChar')); %[output:4d7086bd]
xlabel("Amino Acid"); %[output:4d7086bd]
ylabel("Frequency"); %[output:4d7086bd]
title("PKA Catalytic Subunit (P17612) — Residue Composition"); %[output:4d7086bd]
%%
%[text] ## Section 5: Visualization of 2D Structures of Top Hits
%[text] ### Structure Visualization in Drug Discovery Reports
%[text] 2D structure diagrams are indispensable for medicinal chemists to confirm scaffold identity and assess synthetic feasibility at a glance.
%[text] Visualizing top hits allows for the confirmation of the following three points:
%[text] - Scaffold diversity (whether top candidates are biased towards the same framework)
%[text] - Structural relationship with known KI
%[text] - Presence of PAINS (pan-assay interference compounds) alerts \
%[text] PAINS are compounds with reactive functional groups that can cause false positives in biochemical assays, and their early removal is recommended.
TOP_N   = 10;
topHits = resultTbl(1:min(TOP_N, height(resultTbl)), :);
logInfo("R04 Sec5: Generating 2D structure images for top %d hits.", TOP_N); %[output:934b467e]
for k = 1:height(topHits) %[output:group:3faac842]
    try
        mol_k = emk.mol.fromSmiles(topHits.SMILES(k));
        figure("Name", sprintf("R04 Sec5: Hit %02d %s", k, topHits.Name(k))); %[output:82f9d683] %[output:6180955d] %[output:40631020] %[output:9d27f8b7] %[output:0710abda] %[output:1c8461f0] %[output:89d2ee20] %[output:4467ffd6] %[output:2ffcd8d2] %[output:3ecd6b6a]
        emk.viz.draw2d(mol_k, Width=300, Height=250, ... %[output:82f9d683] %[output:6180955d] %[output:40631020] %[output:9d27f8b7] %[output:0710abda] %[output:1c8461f0] %[output:89d2ee20] %[output:4467ffd6] %[output:2ffcd8d2] %[output:3ecd6b6a]
            Title=sprintf("%d. %s CS=%.3f | Sim=%.3f | MW=%.0f | LogP=%.1f", ... %[output:82f9d683] %[output:6180955d] %[output:40631020] %[output:9d27f8b7] %[output:0710abda] %[output:1c8461f0] %[output:89d2ee20] %[output:4467ffd6] %[output:2ffcd8d2] %[output:3ecd6b6a]
                k, topHits.Name(k), topHits.CompositeScore(k), ... %[output:82f9d683] %[output:6180955d] %[output:40631020] %[output:9d27f8b7] %[output:0710abda] %[output:1c8461f0] %[output:89d2ee20] %[output:4467ffd6] %[output:2ffcd8d2] %[output:3ecd6b6a]
                topHits.MaxSim(k), topHits.MolWt(k), topHits.LogP(k))); %[output:82f9d683] %[output:6180955d] %[output:40631020] %[output:9d27f8b7] %[output:0710abda] %[output:1c8461f0] %[output:89d2ee20] %[output:4467ffd6] %[output:2ffcd8d2] %[output:3ecd6b6a]
    catch ex
        logWarn("R04: Could not render %s: %s", topHits.Name(k), ex.message);
    end
end %[output:group:3faac842]
%[text] Check the quality of top hits with the PAINS filter.
logInfo("R04 Sec5: Checking for PAINS alerts ..."); %[output:80aa4cf6]
nHits       = height(topHits);
isPains     = false(nHits, 1);
painsAlerts = strings(nHits, 1);
for k = 1:nHits
    try
        mol_k      = emk.mol.fromSmiles(topHits.SMILES(k));
        filterInfo = emk.filter.pains(mol_k);
        isPains(k) = filterInfo.isPains;
        if filterInfo.isPains
            painsAlerts(k) = strjoin(filterInfo.alerts, "; ");
            logWarn("  PAINS alert for %s: %s", topHits.Name(k), painsAlerts(k));
        end
    catch
        % pains filter not available -- skip silently
    end
end
nPains = sum(isPains);
if nPains > 0 %[output:group:5a677b16]
    logWarn("R04 Sec5: PAINS alerts found in %d out of %d top hits.", nPains, nHits);
else
    logInfo("R04 Sec5: No PAINS alerts in top %d hits.", nHits); %[output:28dcfe15]
end %[output:group:5a677b16]
%%
%[text] ## Section 6: Exporting Hit Report
%[text] ### Components of a Reproducible Hit Report
%[text] In a computational drug discovery pipeline, it is important to record all information in the report to reproduce the results.
%[text] In this section, we output a ranked list of candidates in CSV and JSON formats, along with metadata including the reference inhibitors used, screening library, and scoring weights.
%[text] All outputs are saved in a timestamped directory via `makeRunDir()` to prevent results from being overwritten with each execution.
runDir = makeRunDir("Prefix", "r04_protein_ligand");
logInfo("R04 Sec6: Outputting report to %s.", runDir); %[output:98e4440a]
csvPath = fullfile(runDir, "r04_kinase_ligand_hits.csv");
writetable(resultTbl, csvPath);
logInfo("  All ranked results -> %s", csvPath); %[output:29a59b38]
top10Path = fullfile(runDir, "r04_top10_hits.csv");
writetable(topHits, top10Path);
logInfo("  Top 10 hits        -> %s", top10Path); %[output:537ad774]
meta.scriptVersion       = "R04 v1.0";
meta.runDate             = char(datetime("now", Format="yyyy-MM-dd HH:mm:ss"));
meta.referenceInhibitors = cellstr(refNames);
meta.libraryFile         = DATA_FILE;
meta.nLibrary            = nLib;
meta.nParsed             = nValid;
meta.fpRadius            = FP_RADIUS;
meta.fpNBits             = FP_NBITS;
meta.weights.similarity  = W_SIM;
meta.weights.property    = W_PROP;
meta.weights.leProxy     = W_LE;
meta.nHitsAbove04        = sum(maxSimScores > 0.40);
meta.nHitsAbove05        = sum(maxSimScores > 0.50);
meta.topHitName          = char(resultTbl.Name(1));
meta.topHitScore         = resultTbl.CompositeScore(1);
metaPath = fullfile(runDir, "run_meta.json");
fid = fopen(metaPath, "w");
fprintf(fid, "%s\n", jsonencode(meta, PrettyPrint=true));
fclose(fid);
logInfo("  Execution metadata -> %s", metaPath); %[output:44fcbb45]
logInfo("R04 Sec6: Screening Summary"); %[output:264c6510]
logInfo("  Library size       : %d", nLib); %[output:0e0e4335]
logInfo("  Parsing success    : %d (%.1f%%)", nValid, 100*nValid/nLib); %[output:6f671b55]
logInfo("  Hits (Sim > 0.40)  : %d (%.1f%%)", sum(maxSimScores>0.40), 100*sum(maxSimScores>0.40)/nValid); %[output:8e641e52]
logInfo("  Hits (Sim > 0.50)  : %d (%.1f%%)", sum(maxSimScores>0.50), 100*sum(maxSimScores>0.50)/nValid); %[output:3ce3fe21]
logInfo("  Top hit            : %s (Score = %.4f)", resultTbl.Name(1), resultTbl.CompositeScore(1)); %[output:004b03da]
logInfo("  Nearest reference KI: %s", resultTbl.BestRefKI(1)); %[output:434cf9c8]
logInfo("R04 Complete."); %[output:0c4d481c]
%%
%[text] ## Summary
%[text] In this script, we implemented a workflow to identify drug repositioning candidates using ligand-based virtual screening (LBVS) without 3D docking.
%[text] **Section 1 — Chemical Space Profiling of Kinase Inhibitors**
%[text] - Calculated MW, LogP, and TPSA for 5 approved kinase inhibitors (including Imatinib) and constructed a median profile of the reference space.
%[text] - Confirmed that many KIs are located in the "bRo5" region, exceeding Ro5 (Lipinski's Rule of Five), with a larger molecular weight than classical oral drugs. \
%[text] 
%[text] **Section 2 — Tanimoto Similarity Screening**
%[text] - Compared 200 FDA drugs with 5 reference KIs using the Tanimoto coefficient $T(q,d) = \\frac{|q \\cap d|}{|q \\cup d|}$ and calculated the maximum similarity $\\text{maxSim}$.
%[text] - Compounds with a threshold of 0.40 or higher emerged as strong candidates sharing the same scaffold as known KIs. \
%[text] 
%[text] **Section 3 — Multi-Criteria Composite Scoring**
%[text] - Ranked using a composite score combining structural similarity (weight 0.4), physicochemical property match (weight 0.4), and ligand efficiency surrogate index LE (weight 0.2).
%[text] - Created a more reliable candidate list through a multifaceted evaluation including ADMET properties, which may be overlooked by single indices. \
%[text] 
%[text] **Section 4 — Protein Sequence Annotation**
%[text] - Identified the DFG motif (activation loop) and P-loop (GxGxxG) from the FASTA sequence of human PKA (UniProt P17612), confirming the sequence characteristics of the kinase binding pocket.
%[text] - Understood the structural background that Type I inhibitors bind in DFG-In and Type II inhibitors (such as Imatinib) bind in DFG-Out conformation. \
%[text] 
%[text] **Section 5 — 2D Structure Visualization and Quality Filtering**
%[text] - Visually confirmed scaffolds in 2D structure diagrams of top hits and evaluated scaffold diversity.
%[text] - Detected biochemically assay-interfering compounds using PAINS filters, improving the quality of the hit list. \
%[text] 
%[text] **Section 6 — Reproducible Report Generation**
%[text] - Recorded metadata such as scoring weights and libraries used in JSON, saving all artifacts in a timestamped directory.
%[text] - Output management with `makeRunDir()` allows accumulation of reproducible comparative experiments with different weight settings. \

